n Society. Since the transitional period between the mid-1970s and mid-1980s, it has established a discourse which combines identity with class position and is structured around the political terms indigenous sovereignty, nationality, territoriality, plural nationality, interculturality, and »the good life«.Philipp Altmann shows how this discourse stands in opposition to the colonial structuring of society and its effects - such as discrimination and inequality - and is therefore to be understood as decolonial.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aIndians of South AmericazEcuador. 0aIndigenous peopleszEcuador. 0aPostcolonialism. 0aSocial movements. 4aDiskurs. 4aEcuador. 4aEntwicklungssoziologie. 4aKolonialität der Macht. 4aLateinamerika. 4aPolitikwissenschaft. 4aPostkolonialismus. 4aSoziale Bewegungen. 4aZivilgesellschaft. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civics & Citizenship.2bisacsh  aCivil Society.  aLatin America.  aPolitical Science.  aPostcolonialism.  aSociology of Development.0 cprintz978383762570740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/transcript.9783839425701?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783839425701zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783839425701/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA